{"add":{"doc":{"id":"01686393096cecd46609075350d1481f17e1f482e7fa164c647e4626a4fb07c2","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/2a/Products_exported_by_Romania.svg/220px-Products_exported_by_Romania.svg.png","previous":["After 1989 the country experienced a decade of economic instability and decline, led in part by an obsolete industrial base and a lack of structural reform. From 2000 onwards, however, the Romanian economy was transformed into one of relative macroeconomic stability, characterised by high growth, low unemployment and declining inflation. In 2006, according to the Romanian Statistics Office, GDP growth in real terms was recorded at 7.7%, one of the highest rates in Europe.[177] However, a recession following the global financial crisis of 2008–2009 forced the government was forced to borrow externally, including an IMF €20bn bailout program.[178] GDP has been growing by over 2% each year since.[179] According to IMF, the GDP per capita purchasing power parity grew from $14,875 in 2007 to an estimated $19,397 in 2014.[174] Romania still has one of the lowest net average monthly wage in the EU of €540 in 2012,[180] and an inflation of 3.7% in 2013.[181] Unemployment in Romania was at 7% in 2012, which is very low compared to other EU countries.[182]"],"after":["Industrial output growth reached 6.5% year-on-year in February 2013, the highest in the EU-27.[183] The largest local companies include carmaker Automobile Dacia, Petrom, Rompetrol, Ford Romania, Electrica, Romgaz, RCS & RDS and Banca Transilvania.[184] Exports have increased substantially in the past few years, with a 13% annual rise in exports in 2010. Romania's main exports are cars, software, clothing and textiles, industrial machinery, electrical and electronic equipment, metallurgic products, raw materials, military equipment, pharmaceuticals, fine chemicals, and agricultural products (fruits, vegetables, and flowers). Trade is mostly centred on the member states of the European Union, with Germany and Italy being the country's single largest trading partners. The account balance in 2012 was estimated to be −4.52% of the GDP.[185]"]}}}